                        "type": "text",
                        "data": [
                            {
                                "tagType": "h2",
                                "tagHTML": "Punya (Virtue) and P√§p (Sin)"
                            },
                            {
                                "tagType": "p",
                                "tagHTML": "As long as a soul is embodied, it's always performing some activity (physical or mental). These activities attract karma."
                            },
                            {
                                "tagType": "div",
                                "tagHTML": "<div class='grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 text-center mt-4'><div class='p-6 bg-green-100 rounded-xl'><h3 class='text-xl font-bold text-green-800'>Punya (Virtue)</h3><p>Meritorious or virtuous deeds (<strong>Shubh</strong>) done with good intentions lead to Punya. This results in happy and comfortable situations, like good health and a beautiful body.</p></div><div class='p-6 bg-red-100 rounded-xl'><h3 class='text-xl font-bold text-red-800'>P√§p (Sin)</h3><p>Evil or vicious acts (<strong>Ashubh</strong>) lead to P√§p. This results in unhappy and miserable situations, like illness and poverty.</p></div></div>"
                            },
                            {
                                "tagType": "p",
                                "tagHTML": "Crucially, it's the <strong>intention</strong> behind an act, not just the act itself, that determines the type of karma acquired."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "accordian",
                        "data": {
                            "title": "The Story of the Two Monks",
                            "items": [
                                {
                                    "header": "The Story of the Two Monks",
                                    "content": "<p class='mb-4'>This story shows how intention is more important than action. Two monks, Suresh muni and Raman muni, came to a flooded river where a young girl was afraid to cross.</p><ol class='list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2'><li><strong class='text-blue-600'>Suresh muni</strong>, seeing her distress, helped her across the river, even carrying her when the water got deep. His intention was pure help, with no attachment or passion. He let go of the girl and the thought of her immediately.</li><li><strong class='text-red-600'>Raman muni</strong> objected to the physical contact, but he himself kept thinking about the girl and the act for an hour afterward, creating passionate thoughts in his mind.</li></ol><p class='mt-4 font-bold text-center'>In this case, Suresh muni earned Punya for his selfless help, while Raman muni, despite not touching the girl, acquired P√§p due to his impure thoughts and intentions.</p>"
                                }
                            ]
                        }
